  "text": "To ensure high-quality data collection across all centers that implant MCS devices, the National Heart, Lung, and Blood Institute issued a request for proposals to create a national database. In 2005, the University of Alabama was awarded a 5-year contract, which led to the formation of the Interagency Registry for Mechanically Assisted Circulatory Support (INTERMACS) [CITATION_1] . This registry was created with the goals of refining patient selection to maximize outcomes with MCS devices, identifying risk factors and predictors of outcomes, developing best-practice guidelines to reduce complications, guiding improvements in technology, and guiding clinical testing and approval of new devices.",
